{
  "doc_id": "52346",
  "text": "Tachyzoites from T. gondii type I virulent strains RH-YFP [CITATION_1] and RH [CITATION_2] , BK [CITATION_3] , type II avirulent strains ME49 [CITATION_4] , NTE [CITATION_5] and PRU-YFP [CITATION_6] , and type III avirulent strain CTG [CITATION_7] were maintained by serial passage in confluent monolayers of HS27 cells [CITATION_8] . Tachyzoites from T. gondii transgenic strains CTG Ble (a type III strain containing a Ble R selectable marker as a control), CTG L1 (CTG expressing a kinase-dead mutant form (ROP18-D394A) of the type I GT-1 allele of ROP18 [CITATION_9] , and CTG V1 (CTG expressing an active form of the type I GT-1 allele of ROP18) [CITATION_10] were passaged in HS27 cells as described for the other T. gondii strains. All tachyzoites were used immediately after harvest for inoculation of untreated, IFNc-stimulated, and/or transiently transfected fibroblasts at a multiplicity of infection of 5 to 10 [CITATION_11] .",
